and":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, England","East Hatley Manor, East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1450–1536":"1450–1536","1455–1488":"1455–1488","1480–Male":"1480–Deceased","1430–1504":"1430–1504","1430–1460":"1430–1460","1536":"1536","1488":"1488","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1504":"1504","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, England","East Hatley Manor, East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Castell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Roberto, Amarilys, Carlos, Eduardo, Estevan, Francisco, Guadalupe, Humberto, Jorge, Manuel, Mateo, Pablo.","English and Scottish: variant of   Castle  .","Manx: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Asgaill</i> ‘son of <i>Ásketill</i>’, an Old Norse personal name composed of the elements <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’. The Manx surname is cognate with Scottish Gaelic   McAskill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Castille","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcee, Antoine, Armand, Maudry, Michel, Monique, Normand, Remy, Renella.","Americanized form of Catalan   Castell  , under the French influence in LA.","French: habitational name from the French name for Castile in Spain (see   Castilla  )."]},{"name":"Castle","meanings":["English: topographic name from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>castel</i> ‘castle, fortified building or set of buildings’, especially the residence of a feudal lord (from Late Latin <i>castellum</i>, a diminutive of <i>castrum</i> ‘fort, Roman walled city’). The name would also have denoted a servant who lived and worked at such a place, or someone who had an obligation to provide services or rent to a castle."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Castell was born in 1450, in Cambridgeshire, England, his father, Robert Castell Sr., was 21 and his mother, Constance Haward, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Millicent Hengrave. He died in 1536, in East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 86."},"et":{"1450–1536":"1450–1536","1455–1488":"1455–1488","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1430–1504":"1430–1504","1430–1460":"1430–1460","1536":"1536","1488":"1488","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1504":"1504","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, England","East Hatley Manor, East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1450–1536":"1450–1536","1455–1488":"1455–1488","1480–Male":"1480–Kuollut","1430–1504":"1430–1504","1430–1460":"1430–1460","1536":"1536","1488":"1488","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1504":"1504","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, England","East Hatley Manor, East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1450–1536":"1450–1536","1455–1488":"1455–1488","1480–Male":"1480–Décédé","1430–1504":"1430–1504","1430–1460":"1430–1460","1536":"1536","1488":"1488","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1504":"1504","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre","East Hatley Manor, East Hatley, South Cambridgeshire district, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"East Hatley, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robe